<p>If we go by the usual schedule, we’re probably a little under three months out from this year’s Worldwide Developers Conference—chances are it’ll be announced before the end of this very month.</p>
<p>It promises to be quite the event.</p>
<p>That’s in no small part because Apple’s found itself in an unusual position this year: the company has already copped to the fact that some of the most impressive features from last year’s WWDC keynote—Siri’s ability to use personal context and take action in various apps—<a href="https://www.macworld.com/article/2631137/apple-is-delaying-the-only-apple-intelligence-feature-everyone-wanted.html">will not arrive on time</a>, and we don’t know exactly <em>when</em> they might ship—if ever.</p>
<p>So when Tim Cook greets the in-person crowd and fires up the keynote video, what exactly are we going to see, and how’s it going to play?</p>
